AGI - The space capsule of the Crew-10 mission of SpaceX> is successfully docked at the International Space Station (Iss) > with the aim of giving the change to four astronauts, including Suni Williams and Butch Wilmore>, who were in the space lab for a week and were blocked for over nine months due to failures to the Boeing spaceship with which they had arrived.
<div </div
The tenth commercial crew of Nasa and Elon Musk's company automatically hooked to Iss a handful of minutes after midnight in the States, after leaving yesterday afternoon from the Kennedy Space Center in Central Florida, driven by a Falcon 9 rocket and after a two-day delay due, in part, to a hydraulic problem in the launch tower.
<div </div
Williams and Wilmore will leave for their return trip in a few days. You don't know exactly when because at least until Wednesday the transfer of deliveries must be completed inside the station.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
At that point you will have to monitor the weather conditions of the place where the amalgamation is expected, not far from the coasts of Florida. Together with them there will be cosmonauts&nbsp;Nick Hague >e&nbsp;&nbsp;Aleksandr Gorbunov,>&nbsp;The Crew-10 transported within it the commander Anne McClain > and the pilot Nichole Ayers>, both of Nasa; The Japanese Takuya Onishi>, agency Jaxa, and Russian cosmonaut Kirill Peskov, > by Roscosmos.&nbsp;&nbsp;
